<font color="#FF0000">COMMENTS FOR RICHARD</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug  6  0:01:53 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
After wandering around these pages for a while, and thrashing things out with many people, I have come to a personal realization that what individuals *did* in response to the Vietnam War, such as those who cut and ran, is truly a matter for their own conscious. I do not expect these individuals to change their views any more that will I when it comes to the imperatives of combat. I except those whose religious way of life and sincere convictions took them on another path.<br><br>
Richard, your post brought home a reminder of a center of my discontent. Clemency for those who chose not to serve in any capacity for whatever personal reason not customarily accepted by society, invalidates the service, sacrifice, and honor of those who did, and the ultimate sacrifice of those whose names appear on The Wall. This is the ultimate tragedy, and the ultimate slap in the face for doing that which was expected of us as citizens. <br><br>
For this reason, I find it very difficult to understand the rationale behind your comment:<br><br>
&quot;...never dreaming that it would take so long...and take such a heavy toll on the kids that were there...&quot;<br><br>
The toll on those &quot;kids&quot; is still extracted by a grim reaper, these pages being full of the continuing carnage of the Vietnam Vortex for both Veterans, and their families. I am one of those &quot;kids&quot;, now 50, caught in the psychological time warp that afflicts many Vietnam Veterans. Be advised, we were not born the way we are now. We were made that way. Many returned from Vietnam as &quot;old men&quot;, empty as sack cloth and ashes, their humanity stripped away.<br><br>
I invite you to visit a Veteran's Hospital and view first hand the horror of sacrifice so invalidated by politicians in the &quot;clemency&quot; process that followed the War. It makes  me sick.<br><br>
I am interested in exploring your motives for your personal course of action. Your comments so far provide no answers.   
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


